Major Types of Igneous Bodies

1. Plutonic (Intrusive) Bodies:

  • Batholiths: Large, irregular, deep-seated bodies covering hundreds of square kilometers.
  • Stocks: Smaller versions of batholiths.
  • Laccoliths: Mushroom-shaped bodies that cause doming of overlying strata.
  • Dikes: Tabular, discordant bodies that cut across rock layers.
  • Sills: Tabular, concordant bodies that intrude parallel to rock layers.

Source: Winter, J. (2014)

Volcanic (Extrusive) Bodies

2. Volcanic (Extrusive) Bodies:

  • Lava Flows: Thin, sheet-like bodies formed by low-viscosity basaltic magma.
  • Volcanic Domes: Steep-sided masses of viscous rhyolitic or andesitic magma.
  • Pyroclastic Flows: Deposits from explosive eruptions, forming extensive, poorly sorted layers.

Source: Winter, J. (2014)
